outputs:
{"answer": "Certainly! Two-factor authentication (2FA) enhances security by requiring users to provide an additional form of identification beyond just a password or PIN during the login process.

Imagine having a door that requires not only a key to open it, but also your driver’s license or fingerprint to open it securely. That way, even if someone gets into the door without a key or a fingerprint, they won’t be able to bypass the security measures.

In 2FA, you're essentially adding an extra layer of authentication that is independent from your password and PIN, thus making it much harder for attackers to gain unauthorized access."}

